<div class="container">
    <h1>HTTP Part 2</h1>
    <p>This section expands on the basics of HTTP by explaining headers, query parameters, POST requests, and how clients send data to the server.</p>

    <h2>HTTP Headers</h2>
    <p>Headers provide metadata about the request or response. Examples include:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>User-Agent:</strong> identifies the client software (browser, app, etc.).</li>
        <li><strong>Content-Type:</strong> specifies the type of data sent in a request or received in a response.</li>
        <li><strong>Authorization:</strong> used for sending authentication tokens.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Query Parameters</h2>
    <p>Clients can pass data via the URL using query parameters:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-http">
GET /search?query=weather&city=Skopje HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
    </code></pre>
    <p>This request asks the server to search for "weather" in "Skopje".</p>

    <h2>POST Requests</h2>
    <p>POST is used to send data to the server, often for creating or updating resources:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-http">
POST /users HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "name": "John Doe",
    "email": "john@example.com"
}
    </code></pre>
    <p>The server will process this JSON data and respond accordingly.</p>

